PUH-BrianMartell pair-instability supernovae (PISNe) are the complete self-destruction of very massive stars (140260 M)  no black hole or neutron star remnant. The core gets so hot (~10^9 K) that gamma rays create electron-positron pairs, pressure drops, collapse triggers runaway oxygen/silicon burning, and the whole star explodes with ~10^52 erg energy (100 normal SN). Nucleosynthesis details:   Dominated by explosive oxygen/silicon burning  huge yields of even-Z elements: O, Si, S, Ar, Ca (up to 100 M oxygen per event).   Odd-even pattern: Even elements overproduced, odd (Na, Al, P) suppressed relative normal SNe.   Iron-group (Ni, Fe) very low  explosive burning stops before complete silicon to iron.   Unique signature: High [O/Fe], low [/Fe] for heavier  (Si-S), distinct from core-collapse SNe. Relate to PUH v25: Rebound creates many very massive stars early (high  folded knots rapid amalgamation). PISNe frequent primordial
